Documentation                                    Preprocessing                                                                                                                                                    Skip to end of metadata                                                                                                                                         Created by  Unknown User (cs175) , last modified on Jul 17, 2012                  Go to start of metadata                                                                                                                    Collapse all            Expand all       Collapse all                                                                                                                                        After a scan has been completed, go to the CBI site and download the data. I chose these parameters:  After some time, the reconstruction will be complete and the files can be copied from CBI User Data to the /data directory by Connect to Server via the Finder menu here:    Pre-Processing fMRI Data Begin by making the appropriate directories in the /data folder for your study, for example, mgrs. Within mgrs, make another folder for the subject, ie. mgrs_03 for subject 3. Then make the following dir's within your subject folder. In terminal, you may also go into the new subject's dir and paste this command to make the proper directory structure:      [ chad @ sandman /data/mgrs/mgrs_03 ] tree.sh /data/mgrs/mgrs_04 |-anatomy |-experiment |-eyefiles |-funcdata |-mgl |-models |-rawdata |-reachfiles |-stats |-tesfiles Copy your data from CBI into the rawdata dir:           Icon                [ chad @ sandman /data/mgrs/mgrs_03/rawdata ] pwd /data/mgrs/mgrs_03/rawdata             This will make your life easy. Next make copies of your *unwarped* .nii EPI files (not the *_rho.nii files) from rawdata to funcdata, such as:           Icon                [ chad @ sandman /data/mgrs/mgrs_03/rawdata/11+MocapEpi ] ls 120711115809.nii* 120711115809_rho.nii* [ chad @ sandman /data/mgrs/mgrs_03/rawdata/11+MocapEpi ] pwd /data/mgrs/mgrs_03/rawdata/11+MocapEpi               Using the Terminal enter, this command. I chose to delete the first 4 volumes. You may use SPM8 to view the histogram and determine where your spike is. In our Mocap study, we added 8 seconds, 4 TRs, to the beginning of each trial to allow for the spike when starting EPIs.                   fslroi "filename" "newfilename, IE 'mgs_01.nii'" 4 186             This chops off 4 volumes containing the spike and renames file in one step. For example, mgr_03.nii for the 3rd epi which in this case was a reach. Do this for each file renaming for saccade or reach. You can also specify a path from rawdata to funcdata and have fslroi put the edited file there. More examples: t_mgs_01 & t_mgs_02.nii Running Pablo's Data Quality Check Tools. Fix spikes if necessary. There may be some hidden files breaking the Data Quality Checking scripts, see this section for more:      Slice Timing We must do slice timing corrections first, contrary to the documentation So we'll be working with SPM8 from within Matlab. I'm using 7.14, but start whatever matlab you prefer Documentation for SPM8 is under /hyper/procedures From the matlab prompt, enter spm <return> In SPM, run slice timing correction with 'slicetiming.mat', which was created 2012 07 12. Add files from funcdata Realignment In SPM click on 'Realign'. In the Batch Editor, add the files you edited from funcdata and remove the ",1" from the end of the filenames. After Timing Correction & Realignment have completed, you should have a bunch of mat files that begin with the rt and t. The t files were output from the timing correction step and the rt files have Co Registration Click on co-registration in spm Leave funcdata to rawdata,  cp from rawdata to anatory, copy 2D_mp rage inplane.nii copy t1_sag into the anatomy directory called, 'anat.nii' in anatomy you will have anat.nii and inplane.nii when done Then do the same with the mean_ and ranat.nii Adjust the transparency to see how they overlay Plot Movement Params In anatomy directory, run fslview anat.nii & Run fslview inplane.nii & These will yield the rimplane.nii, open it with 'fslview rimplane.nii &' in Terminal Segmentation Click Segment In data directory select, ranat.nii Sampling Distance should be '2' (these are in the slicealign.mat file) segment_03.mat could be rerun on other subjects Normalization Select Normalize (Write) Select the _en.mat in funcdata Select the mean and all the 'rt*' files In the Bounding Box, select, '-78, -112, -70' use 70 instead of 50 to get rid of the cerebellum, these are in the Indirect Normalization settings Look at wrt for normalized realigned && time           Icon                Batching .mat files with SPM sequences are in a dir called 'batchmats'            in MNI space you can determine a coordinate space value to put in your journal article Smoothing Click Smooth You always smooth the images that begin with the w's, ie. 'wrt*' We have 8, we'll use 6, ie. 6 6 6, because 8 is a little too big. You can always go back and smooth more later. Smoothing drops the floor on noise and allows for the areas, ie. a sulcus location, to overlap.                                                       No labels                                                       1 Child Page                                                       Page:     Tree.sh                                                                                                                                                                                     Powered by Atlassian Confluence 5.6.6 , Team Collaboration Software      Printed by Atlassian Confluence 5.6.6, Team Collaboration Software.
